{
  "text": "Sequencing reads were mapped to all known promoters in any pTpA library using Bowtie2 [CITATION_1] . Only promoters with at least 20 reads in the input DNA and 1 read in the MNase data were kept for subsequent analysis. Input and MNase counts were scaled within each sample to yield counts per million (CPM) per promoter and the log ratio of MNase to input was compared between replicates and to the model's predicted occupancy, corresponding to log(1-predicted accessibility). To combine MNase replicates, the log ratio of MNase to input was averaged for promoters present in both samples -those in only one sample were ignored. Similarly, pairwise correlations between samples in Fig. 3a reflect only the promoters common to both samples, and all promoters within the sample when comparing to the model's predictions.",
  "correct_citation": {
    "[CITATION_1]": "205420407"
  },
  "bib_entries": {
    "205420407": {
      "title": "Fast gapped-read alignment with Bowtie 2",
      "abstract": "As the rate of sequencing increases, greater throughput is demanded from read aligners. The full-text minute index is often used to make alignment very fast and memory-efficient, but the approach is ill-suited to finding longer, gapped alignments. Bowtie 2 combines the strengths of the full-text minute index with the flexibility and speed of hardware-accelerated dynamic programming algorithms to achieve a combination of high speed, sensitivity and accuracy."
    }
  }
}